===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[shine]]; to make a surface very [[smooth]] or shiny by rubbing, cleaning, or grinding.
#: {{ux|en|He '''polished''' up the chrome until it gleamed.}}
# {{senseid|en|refine; improve imperfections from}}{{lb|en|transitive}} To [[refine]]; remove imperfections from.
#: {{ux|en|The band has '''polished''' its performance since the last concert.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1699|author={{w|Sir William Temple, 1st Baronet|William Temple}}|title=Heads designed for an essay on conversations|url=http://essays.quotidiana.org/temple/heads_for_conversation/
|passage=Study gives strength to the mind; conversation, grace: the first apt to give stiffness, the other suppleness: one gives substance and form to the statue, the other '''polishes''' it.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[apply]] [[shoe polish]] to shoes.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become smooth, as from friction; to receive a gloss; to take a smooth and glossy surface.
#: {{ux|en|Steel '''polishes''' well.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=a. 1626|author=w:Francis Bacon|title=Inquisitions touching the compounding of metals
|passage=The other [gold], whether it will polish so well Wherein for the latter [brass] it is probable it will}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[refine]]; to wear off the rudeness, coarseness, or rusticity of; to make elegant and polite.
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=9|passage=Arts that '''polish''' Life.|year=1873}}

